passages.text: August 28, 2025 05:12 AM GMT
China Equity Strategy | Asia Pacific

MSCI China 2Q earnings beat consensus on weighted surprise and improved vs. 1Q, with in- line results by company count. A- share earnings missed by company count and weakened vs. 1Q, though weighted surprise remains in- line. Communication Services, Consumer Discretionary, and Financials stood out.
Takeaways from interim review of Chinese equities' 2Q25 earnings season (based on \(55\%\) of MSCI China and \(29\%\) of MSCI China A Onshore market cap reported):

For MSCI China, reported earnings are largely in line with consensus if measured by the number of companies \((- 2.4\%\) vs. \(- 3.8\%\) in 1Q25) but have beaten consensus so far if measured by weighted surprise \((+9.6\%\) vs. \(+3.1\%\) in 1Q25). While it's worth noting that results releases are still in the early stage, some big players like Meituan haven't been included in our mid- cut result; we will see if these trends can be sustained through the end of 2Q25 earnings season.

For A- shares, reported earnings fell short of consensus forecasts by number of companies \((- 11.6\%\) vs. \(- 4.8\%\) in 1Q25) but were largely in line by weighted surprise \((+0.0\%\) vs. \(+3.3\%\) in 1Q25). We will see if these trends can broaden out.

In revenue terms, both A- shares and MSCI China have missed consensus revenue estimates by number of companies but posted in- line results by weighted surprise. In general, reported revenues have missed consensus more, relative to earnings, due to better cost control and self- help strategy.

Sector observations: Communication Services, Consumer Discretionary, Financials posted solid results, while Energy, Materials, Real Estate and Utilities for A- shares missed on both number of companies and weighted earnings.

Note: As of August 26, 2025, 217 constituents out of 557 in MSCI China had reported 2Q25 results. Our analysis of MSCI China earnings surprises is based on constituent companies that have reasonable quality data for consensus estimates, comprising 209 companies in MSCI China, representing \(39\%\) of the index by number of companies and \(55\%\) by index weight.

1) At the aggregate index level, reported earnings are largely in line with consensus forecasts by number of companies (-2.4%) and beat consensus by a moderate margin if measured by weighted surprise (+9.6%): See Exhibit 4. This is a better set of results than in 1Q25, where we had an in-line result measured by number of companies (-3.8%) and weighted surprise (+3.1%). We will see if these trends can hold until the end of 2Q25 earnings season.

2) Sectors with earnings beats: Out of the sectors with at least \(30\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Consumer Discretionary posted a double beat by both number of companies and weighted surprise.

- With \(34\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Consumer Discretionary has beat consensus earnings by both number of companies and weighted surprise. Main contributors include XPeng, and PDD. 
- With \(75\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Healthcare has beat consensus earnings by weighted surprise. Genscript Biotech and Be One led the beat.
3) Sectors with earnings misses: Out of the sectors with at least \(30\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Industrials and Materials recorded a miss by number of companies.

- With \(50\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Industrials has missed consensus earnings by number of companies and is in line on weighted surprise. ZTO led the miss. 
- With \(70\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Materials has missed consensus earnings by number of companies and is in line on weighted surprise. Zhaojin Mining led the miss.

Note: As of August 26, 2025, 24Q constituents out of 557 in MSCI China had reported 2Q25 results. Our analysis of MSCI China revenue surprises is based on non- financial constituent companies that have reasonable quality data for consensus estimates, comprising 191 companies in MSCI China, representing 43% of the index by number of companies and 51% by index weight.

1) At the aggregate index level, reported revenue has missed consensus by number of companies (-7.9%) so far: The magnitude of net miss narrowed vs. 1Q25 at -16.6%. If measured by weighted surprise, reported revenue has been in line with consensus (+1.3%) in 2Q25.
2) Sector-level beats: Out of the sectors with no less than 30% of sector market cap reported so far, Communication Services, Materials and Real Estate posted net beat by number of companies.

3) Sector-level misses: Out of the sectors with at least 30% of sector market cap reported so far, Consumer Discretionary, Consumer Staples, Industrials and Information Technology posted net miss by number of companies.

Note: We use constituents of MSCI China A Onshore Index as a proxy for the A- share stock universe. As of August 26, 2025, 233 companies in MSCI China A Onshore had reported 2Q25 earnings results. Our analysis of A- share earnings surprises is based on constituent companies that have reasonable quality data for consensus estimates, comprising 146 companies in MSCI China A Onshore, representing \(26\%\) of the index by number of companies and \(29\%\) by index weight.

1) At the aggregate index level, reported earnings fell short of consensus forecasts by number of companies \((-11.6\%)\) and in line by weighted surprise \((+0.0\%)\) : See Exhibit 10. This is a slightly worse result than in 1Q25 as measured by both weighted surprise and number of companies. A- shares 2Q25 earnings season is still in the early stages. We will see if the entire A-share index demonstrate such trends.

2) Sectors with earnings beats: Out of the sectors with at least \(20\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Communication Services posted a net beat by both number of companies and weighted surprise. Consumer Discretionary posted a net beat by number of companies, and was in line by weighted surprise. Healthcare posted a slight net beat by weighted surprise, but recorded a net miss by number of companies.

- With \(54\%\) of sector market cap reported, Communication Services has largely beat consensus earnings by both number of companies and weighted surprise. Key contributors include: Kunlun Tech and 37 Interactive Entertainment.- Consumer Discretionary beat consensus earnings by number of companies and was in line by weighted surprise. Key contributors include: Fuyao Group Glass and Chongqing Changan Auto.
3) Sectors with earnings misses: Out of the sectors with at least \(20\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Materials and Real Estate missed by both number of companies and weighted surprise.

- Materials has posted a net miss by both number of companies and weighted surprise, with \(28\%\) of sector-level market cap reported so far. Key contributors include: Sinomine Resource and Guangzhou Tinci Materials A.- Real Estate has posted a net miss by both measures, with \(38\%\) of sector-level market cap reported so far. Key contributors include: China Vanke and Poly Development & Holdings Group.

Note: We use constituents of MSCI China A Onshore Index as a proxy for the A- share stock universe. As of August 26, 2025, 238 companies in MSCI China A Onshore had reported 2Q25 results. Our analysis of A- share revenue surprises is based on non- financial constituent companies that have reasonable quality data for consensus estimates, comprising 125 companies in MSCI China A Onshore, representing \(26\%\) of the index by number of companies and \(26\%\) by index weight.

1) At the aggregate index level, reported revenue has missed consensus notably by number of companies (-22.4%): The magnitude of the miss is the same as in 1Q25. If measured by weighted surprise, reported revenue has been in line with consensus (-4.7%) so far.

2) Sector-level beats: Out of the sectors with at least \(20\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, no sector has posted a beat. Communication Services have in-line results by both number of companies and weighted surprise.

3) Sector-level misses: Out of the sectors with at least \(20\%\) of sector market cap reported so far, Energy, Information Technology, Materials, Real Estate have missed consensus revenue by both number of companies and weighted surprise.
